	)
	(text "When the switch closes (J2 pin 1 and 2), current is flowing through U4 and U5\nPhotoMOSes until C2 is charged up. U4 will pull the gate of Q1 P-MOSFET low,\nraising the IN+ pin of the 3.7 to 5 V DC converter. U5 is still conducting,\nso C1 will be charged up. As long as it is charged, Q3 N-MOSFET is conducting,\nmaintaining a low gate voltage on Q1 P-MOSFET.\nBecause the boost converter gets activated while C2 is being charged up,\nit will reach a higher voltage than it would on the battery alone.\nDepending on switch quality, it is recommended to choose a capacitance between\n33 to 100 µF to ensure consistent current flow for the activation process.\nThe system remains active as long as the load draws enough current.\nA Raspberry Pi with a 7 inch screen draws about 1.1 A, so 22 mV will be measured\non R1 constantan resistor, while R3 is at 9 mV. In this case, IN+ of U3 comparator\nis lower than IN-, resulting in 0 V output.\nWhen the switch opens, C2 will be discharged, flipping the signal low on the Pi's\npin 16. This will be detected by the python script running in the background, and\na software shutdown is initiated.\nAfter shutdown, the voltage on the shunt drops to 2.2 mV. The comparator signal\nchanges to 5 V, enabling Q2 N-MOSFET with a little delay, thanks to C4 capacitor.\nC1 is discharged through R5 resistor, and in about 24 seconds,\nat 1.2 V gate, Q3 stops conducting, driving the gate of Q1 high,\nwhich stops conducting too.\nThe circuit collapses, and all load is removed from the battery, apart from the\nreal-time clock.\nAfter the initial pulse at startup, C1 gets partially discharged down to 2.63 V,\nuntil the Pi draws full current consistently. R38 will take care of slowly\ncharging up the capacitor again.\nThe same shutdown sequence will occur when the Pi is shut down remotely.\nThe switch has to be turned off and on in order to restart the system.\n\nIn addition to power control, the board contains an USB socket for a trigger switch\nused by the oscilloscope program, a connector forwarding measurements to the AD7606\nmodule, and one channel is permanently set to monitor the battery voltage."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
